And the wall collapsed …
Here's a quiz for history buffs: twenty years ago, the year 1989 was a fateful year marked by three events that all took place on June 4.
Which one do you remember the best and which one had the most consequences for the planet?
a) The brutal repression of Tiananmen Square
b) The death of Ayatollah Khomeini in Iran
c) The elections in Poland
Few respond to that.
Because the events in Beijing and Khomeini's death, which made headlines, eclipsed the victory of the famous opposition union Solidarnosc in the first free election in Eastern Europe since 1946.
However, nothing has contributed more to the collapse of communism in Europe - and consequently to the refounding of the post-war international order.
There will be all sorts of commemorations of the end of communism in the coming months, including the anniversary of the fall of the Berlin Wall in November 1989.
For many people, it was a moment of glory, emblematic of the victory of the West at the end of the Cold War, a victory that one doesn't know where it came from.
But having witnessed the collapse of the Eastern bloc from the beginning, one realizes that the process was long and complex.
The election in Poland was a point of no return, the moment when the movement in favor of change became irreversible.
It had gained strength after a summer of strikes, when the communist leader at the head of Poland, General Jaruzelski, estimated that the country's economic problems were too serious for him to face alone.
Why not call on the Polish opposition, he thought - if not to find a solution - at least to share the responsibility for the situation ?
After six months of negotiations, he concluded a historic agreement: there would be free and fair legislative elections, and Solidarnosc would be able to participate.
The communist leaders (just like Solidarnosc) never for a moment considered the possibility that they might lose.
Not even in their darkest nightmares did they imagine they would be ousted from power.
Yet, that's exactly what happened.
Looking back, it's astonishing that there was any doubt.
Solidarity ran its campaign with its tail between its legs.
A famous poster from a classic western film, The Train Will Be at Station Three Times, was diverted for the occasion. The film was a huge success: it shows Gary Cooper holding a ballot paper instead of a revolver, playing the role of the sheriff.
June 4th was Judgment Day.
On that bright Sunday morning, as spring was giving way to summer, the Polish communists were sent to the slaughterhouse by the voters.
On their last day in power, the Polish communists resorted to a final perversion that turned into an involuntary self-humiliation.
They designed an electoral system in which the Poles, instead of selecting their preferred candidates, had to cross out the names of those they did not want - in other words, all the communists listed on the ballots.
Everywhere you looked, people were getting rid of the detested autocrats.
This was finally the popular uprising that Poland had been waiting for, the revenge for December 1980, when Jaruzelski decreed martial law, banned Solidarnosc, and imprisoned its leaders.
The revolution with the pen!
Handled with style, the pen, which ultimately triumphed over the sword, became the weapon of a glorious revenge.
Certain voters tore their ballots to shreds, thus bringing down the old regime with a decisive blow.
Others were savoring the moment, perhaps taking a drag on a cigarette while crossing out names on the ballots.
"That one put my cousin in prison", Pfft!, "Ah, this apparatchik got rich off our poverty", Pfft!
Pfft!
On the other hand, the communist campaign went almost unnoticed.
In all Warsaw, only two government candidates took the trouble to put up posters.
Most of them counted on their monopoly in the media to get their message across: "Vote Lezek, a good communist".
We can say to his credit that the regime recognized its defeat with remarkable graciousness.
The day after the elections, at three o'clock in the afternoon, Jaruzelski gathered the main party officials to tell them: "Our defeat is total", we must find a political solution".
He meant that he did not want any violence or rigging, the communists would have to live with the result of the vote.
Twenty years later, I am still perplexed.
Those of us who covered Eastern Europe knew that Solidarity was going to win.
We also knew that this peaceful victory would be an example for the rest of the Eastern bloc.
The Polish vote was extremely encouraging for anti-communists everywhere in the world.
Thanks to Poland, what seemed impossible just a few days earlier suddenly became achievable.
There were other signs.
In May, the Hungarian reformers began to dismantle the fences erected on the border with Austria - a hole in the Iron Curtain.
In Moscow, Mikhail Gorbachev spoke of a "common European house" and rejected Brejnev's interventionist doctrine.
However, when the wall fell, the political leaders and experts unanimously recognized it: "We saw nothing coming".
The Cold War lasted so long that any change seemed impossible - until the day freedom burst forth.
